Linear Regression: Public Transit Ridership, Gender, & Income

This report assesses the potential linear relationship between the choice of taking public transit based on the predictors of gender and income/poverty level. We are using 5 year census data for 2018 at both the individual level and aggregated across the Bay Area.

Public transportation has often been associated with lower-income folks who cannot afford a car to travel. Cars can be costly to maintain and fix, and for those who cant afford to take the driving test, public transit is a useful alternative. However, even higher-income professionals benefit from transit systems, especially . In New Orleans, 1/3 of residents who are in poverty take public transportation, compared to close to 10% for other commuters, while in San Diego, those who take transit make half the income of those who can drive. The same article points out that past ACS data has shown connections between low income and transit ridership. There can also be disparity between types of transit, as bus fares are often made up of lower income riders than rail.

Furthermore, in the webinar series Ideas + Action 2020: Public Space by SPUR, a panel regarding Safe Streets raised the question of safety in public spaces and transit in regards to gender, among other identities. Female and non-binary people may feel less safe due to the possibility of assault. The International Transportation Forum launched an entire report on this topic, citing that transportation systems must be redesigned with women in mind.

These findings prompt a multiple regression analysis of the association between income, gender, and whether or not someone takes public transportation. In our case, we focus on low income households, either through their income-poverty ratio for an individual (analysis 1) or whether someone makes under 75K (analysis 2). It should be noted that while ACS 5-year estimates only include male and female sex, a more thorough and equitable analysis would include multiple gender identities as well.

Individual & Household Analysis

We use person-level PUMS data to understanding the relationship. We use SEX (whether someone is male or female), JWTR (mode of transportation used to work), and POVPIP (income-poverty ratio). JWTR lists multiple forms of transportation, and we consider the following as public transit: bus/trolley bus, streetcar/trolley car, subway, railroad, ferryboat, biking, and walking. We do not consider taxicab in this analysis to stay consistent with the non-PUMS analysis below this example, which excludes taxicabs. POVPIP is used as a proxy for individual income in this case, since it includes a more granular estimate of income at the individual level than other PUMS data, which focuses on much larger income buckets or is at the household level. As POVPIP increases, the less in proximity someone is in poverty.

ca_pums <- readRDS("ca_pums.rds")

ca_pumas <-
   pumas("CA", cb = T, progress_bar = F)

bay_county_names <-
  c(
    "Alameda",
    "Contra Costa",
    "Marin",
    "Napa",
    "San Francisco",
    "San Mateo",
    "Santa Clara",
    "Solano",
    "Sonoma"
  )

bay_counties <-
  counties("CA", cb = T, progress_bar = F) %>%
  filter(NAME %in% bay_county_names)

bay_pumas <-
  ca_pumas %>% 
  st_centroid() %>% 
  .[bay_counties, ] %>% 
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>% 
  left_join(ca_pumas %>% select(GEOID10)) %>% 
  st_as_sf()

bay_pums <-
  ca_pums %>% 
  filter(PUMA %in% bay_pumas$PUMACE10)
bay_pums_variables <-
  bay_pums %>%
    mutate(
      transit =
      ifelse(
        JWTR == c(2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 9, 10), #walking, biking, and use of: bus, streetcar, subway, railroad, ferryboat
        1,
        0
      ),
      gender =
      ifelse(
        SEX == 2,
        1,
        0
      )
    )
model_pums <- lm(transit ~  gender  + POVPIP, bay_pums_variables, weights = PWGTP)
summary(model_pums)

The R^2 value is 0.23, which is a very weak correlation at best. This result is probably due to the variety of suburban-urban neighborhoods in the Bay Area, which are all being aggregated together in this example. It may also be due to the variation between income brackets under 75K yearly income, though under 75K can be considered below the poverty line in parts of the Bay. Even if public transit feels unsafe for women, it may not be a complete deterrant and may be the only option for female commuters. There are stronger localized relationships between income, choice of transit, and gender, and zooming in on particular brackets and particular types of transit could yield stronger relationships. Industry and age could also play a role.

Tract Analysis

For this version, we are focused on workers in the Bay Area, using gender and income as indicators and the choice of walking or public transportation as the response variable.

acs_vars_2018_5yr  <-
  readRDS("acs_vars_2018_5yr.rds")

#B08119: public transit by income
bay_tract_transit_income <-
  getCensus(
    name = "acs/acs5",
    vintage = 2018,
    region = "tract:*",
    regionin = "state:06+county:001,013,041,055,075,081,085,095,097",
    vars = c(
      "B08119_001E", #total
      "B08119_037E", #total - walked
      "B08119_028E", #total - public transit
      #for each income level below 75,000
      "B08119_002E", 
      "B08119_003E", 
      "B08119_004E", 
      "B08119_005E", 
      "B08119_006E", 
      "B08119_007E", 
      "B08119_008E"
    )
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    tract = paste0(state, county, tract),
    perc_transit_walk = (B08119_037E + B08119_028E)/B08119_001E,
    perc_under75k = (B08119_002E + B08119_003E + B08119_004E + B08119_005E + B08119_006E + B08119_007E + B08119_008E) / B08119_001E
  ) %>%
  filter(
    !is.na(perc_transit_walk),
    !is.na(perc_under75k)
  )
bay_tract_gender <-
  getCensus(
    name = "acs/acs5",
    vintage = 2018,
    region = "tract:*",
    regionin = "state:06+county:001,013,041,055,075,081,085,095,097",
    vars = c(
      "B08012_001E", #female workers (based on commute time)
      "B08012_027E" #total workers (based on commute time)
    )
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    tract = paste0(state, county, tract),
    perc_women = B08012_027E/B08012_001E
  ) %>%
  filter(
    !is.na(perc_women)
  ) 
gender_income_transit <-
  bay_tract_transit_income %>%
    left_join(bay_tract_gender) 
ggplot() +
  geom_point(
    data = gender_income_transit,
    aes(
      x = perc_women,
      y = perc_transit_walk
    )
  )

ggplot() +
  geom_point(
    data = gender_income_transit,
    aes(
      x = perc_under75k,
      y = perc_transit_walk
    )
  )

The following scatter plot briefly shows the relationship between income (under 75K) or gender (% women) on the x axis and their corresponding y value of % of transit users and walkers per tract value. The distribution of low ridership across the Bay Area may present an issue for our results.

model_total <- lm(perc_transit_walk ~ perc_under75k + perc_women, gender_income_transit)

summary(model_total)

Once again, we see an even smaller R^2 value (0.1578) for the relationship between transit, income, and gender. Since our buckets for income are more general in this example as compared to PUMS data, this may disrupt trends we see based on specific income brackets and have lowered the correlation. In some parts of the Bay, 75K is a smaller threshold for poverty as well, so larger income brackets may bring a larger correlation.

Overall, this particular analysis does not yield a causal relationship, and COVID-19 may further disrupt transportation choices that this data does not capture. The scale of this analysis was also very large, given the attempt to subject the entire Bay Area to analysis, even if transportation systems are only strong in some of the counties. However, understanding barriers to a safe, comfortable public transit experience across demographic is key to designing more equitable systems and will require more qualitative research on local systems.
